#: src/administration/configuration.md:1
msgid "Configuration"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/configuration.md:3
msgid ""
"The configuration is based on the file config.hjson, which is located by "
"default at `config/config.hjson`, or `lemmy.hjson` when using Docker. You "
"can set a different path with the environment variable "
"`LEMMY_CONFIG_LOCATION`."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/configuration.md:5
msgid "Full config with default values"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/configuration.md:7
msgid ""
"```hjson\n"
"{\n"
"  # settings related to the postgresql database\n"
"  database: {\n"
"    # Configure the database by specifying a URI\n"
"    # \n"
"    # This is the preferred method to specify database connection details "
"since\n"
"    # it is the most flexible.\n"
"    # Connection URI pointing to a postgres instance\n"
"    # \n"
"    # This example uses peer authentication to obviate the need for "
"creating,\n"
"    # configuring, and managing passwords.\n"
"    # \n"
"    # For an explanation of how to use connection URIs, see [here][0] in\n"
"    # PostgreSQL's documentation.\n"
"    # \n"
"    # [0]: https://www.postgresql.org/docs/current/libpq-connect."
"html#id-1.7.3.8.3.6\n"
"    uri: \"postgresql:///lemmy?user=lemmy&host=/var/run/postgresql\"\n"
"\n"
"    # or\n"
"\n"
"    # Configure the database by specifying parts of a URI\n"
"    # \n"
"    # Note that specifying the `uri` field should be preferred since it "
"provides\n"
"    # greater control over how the connection is made. This merely exists "
"for\n"
"    # backwards-compatibility.\n"
"    # Username to connect to postgres\n"
"    user: \"string\"\n"
"    # Password to connect to postgres\n"
"    password: \"string\"\n"
"    # Host where postgres is running\n"
"    host: \"string\"\n"
"    # Port where postgres can be accessed\n"
"    port: 123\n"
"    # Name of the postgres database for lemmy\n"
"    database: \"string\"\n"
"    # Maximum number of active sql connections\n"
"    # \n"
"    # A high value here can result in errors \"could not resize shared "
"memory segment\". In this case\n"
"    # it is necessary to increase shared memory size in Docker: https://"
"stackoverflow.com/a/56754077\n"
"    pool_size: 30\n"
"  }\n"
"  # Pictrs image server configuration.\n"
"  pictrs: {\n"
"    # Address where pictrs is available (for image hosting)\n"
"    url: \"http://localhost:8080/\"\n"
"    # Set a custom pictrs API key. ( Required for deleting images )\n"
"    api_key: \"string\"\n"
"    # Backwards compatibility with 0.18.1. False is equivalent to "
"`image_mode: None`, true is\n"
"    # equivalent to `image_mode: StoreLinkPreviews`.\n"
"    # \n"
"    # To be removed in 0.20\n"
"    cache_external_link_previews: true\n"
"    # Specifies how to handle remote images, so that users don't have to "
"connect directly to remote\n"
"    # servers.\n"
"    image_mode: \n"
"      # Leave images unchanged, don't generate any local thumbnails for post "
"urls. Instead the\n"
"      # Opengraph image is directly returned as thumbnail\n"
"      \"None\"\n"
"\n"
"      # or\n"
"\n"
"      # Generate thumbnails for external post urls and store them "
"persistently in pict-rs. This\n"
"      # ensures that they can be reliably retrieved and can be resized using "
"pict-rs APIs. However\n"
"      # it also increases storage usage.\n"
"      # \n"
"      # This is the default behaviour, and also matches Lemmy 0.18.\n"
"      \"StoreLinkPreviews\"\n"
"\n"
"      # or\n"
"\n"
"      # If enabled, all images from remote domains are rewritten to pass "
"through\n"
"      # `/api/v3/image_proxy`, including embedded images in markdown. Images "
"are stored temporarily\n"
"      # in pict-rs for caching. This improves privacy as users don't expose "
"their IP to untrusted\n"
"      # servers, and decreases load on other servers. However it increases "
"bandwidth use for the\n"
"      # local server.\n"
"      # \n"
"      # Requires pict-rs 0.5\n"
"      \"ProxyAllImages\"\n"
"    # Allows bypassing proxy for specific image hosts when using "
"ProxyAllImages.\n"
"    # \n"
"    # imgur.com is bypassed by default to avoid rate limit errors. When "
"specifying any bypass\n"
"    # in the config, this default is ignored and you need to list imgur "
"explicitly. To proxy imgur\n"
"    # requests, specify a noop bypass list, eg `proxy_bypass_domains "
"[\"example.org\"]`.\n"
"    proxy_bypass_domains: [\n"
"      \"i.imgur.com\"\n"
"      /* ... */\n"
"    ]\n"
"    # Timeout for uploading images to pictrs (in seconds)\n"
"    upload_timeout: 30\n"
"    # Resize post thumbnails to this maximum width/height.\n"
"    max_thumbnail_size: 512\n"
"  }\n"
"  # Email sending configuration. All options except login/password are "
"mandatory\n"
"  email: {\n"
"    # Hostname and port of the smtp server\n"
"    smtp_server: \"localhost:25\"\n"
"    # Login name for smtp server\n"
"    smtp_login: \"string\"\n"
"    # Password to login to the smtp server\n"
"    smtp_password: \"string\"\n"
"    # Address to send emails from, eg \"noreply@your-instance.com\"\n"
"    smtp_from_address: \"noreply@example.com\"\n"
"    # Whether or not smtp connections should use tls. Can be none, tls, or "
"starttls\n"
"    tls_type: \"none\"\n"
"  }\n"
"  # Parameters for automatic configuration of new instance (only used at "
"first start)\n"
"  setup: {\n"
"    # Username for the admin user\n"
"    admin_username: \"admin\"\n"
"    # Password for the admin user. It must be between 10 and 60 characters.\n"
"    admin_password: \"tf6HHDS4RolWfFhk4Rq9\"\n"
"    # Name of the site, can be changed later. Maximum 20 characters.\n"
"    site_name: \"My Lemmy Instance\"\n"
"    # Email for the admin user (optional, can be omitted and set later "
"through the website)\n"
"    admin_email: \"user@example.com\"\n"
"  }\n"
"  # the domain name of your instance (mandatory)\n"
"  hostname: \"unset\"\n"
"  # Address where lemmy should listen for incoming requests\n"
"  bind: \"0.0.0.0\"\n"
"  # Port where lemmy should listen for incoming requests\n"
"  port: 8536\n"
"  # Whether the site is available over TLS. Needs to be true for federation "
"to work.\n"
"  tls_enabled: true\n"
"  federation: {\n"
"    # Limit to the number of concurrent outgoing federation requests per "
"target instance.\n"
"    # Set this to a higher value than 1 (e.g. 6) only if you have a huge "
"instance (>10 activities\n"
"    # per second) and if a receiving instance is not keeping up.\n"
"    concurrent_sends_per_instance: 1\n"
"  }\n"
"  prometheus: {\n"
"    bind: \"127.0.0.1\"\n"
"    port: 10002\n"
"  }\n"
"  # Sets a response Access-Control-Allow-Origin CORS header\n"
"  # https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Headers/Access-Control-"
"Allow-Origin\n"
"  cors_origin: \"lemmy.tld\"\n"
"  # Print logs in JSON format. You can also disable ANSI colors in logs with "
"env var `NO_COLOR`.\n"
"  json_logging: false\n"
"}\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/configuration.md:150
msgid "Lemmy-UI configuration"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/configuration.md:152
msgid ""
"Lemmy-UI can be configured using environment variables, detailed in its "
"[README](https://github.com/LemmyNet/lemmy-ui#readme)."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/first_steps.md:1
msgid "First Steps"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/first_steps.md:3
msgid ""
"After you successfully installed Lemmy either [manually with Docker]"
"(install_docker.md) or [automatically with Ansible](install_ansible.md) here "
"are some recommendations for a new administrator of a Lemmy server."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/first_steps.md:5
msgid "Admin Settings"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/first_steps.md:7
msgid ""
"The first thing to do is to go to your admin panel, which can be found by "
"clicking on the cog at the top right next to the search icon. Here you can "
"define a description for your site, so that people know if it is about one "
"specific topic or if all subjects are welcome. You can also add an icon and "
"a banner that define your server, it can for example be the logo of your "
"organization."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/first_steps.md:9
msgid ""
"Take the time to browse through the entire page to discover the different "
"options you have to customize your Lemmy instance, on the same page you can "
"edit your [configuration file](configuration.md), where you can find "
"information about your database, the email used by the server, the "
"federation options or who is the main administrator."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/first_steps.md:11
msgid ""
"It is always good to define another administrator than yourself, in case it "
"is necessary to take actions while you take your best nap. Take a look at "
"the [moderation guide](../users/04-moderation.md) for more information on "
"how to do this."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/first_steps.md:13
msgid "Check that everything is working properly"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/first_steps.md:15
msgid "Email"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/first_steps.md:17
msgid ""
"The easiest way to check that the email is set up correctly is to request a "
"password renewal. You will need to set up an email in your settings if you "
"have not already done so."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/first_steps.md:19
msgid ""
"After that just log out, go to the `Login` page, enter your email in the "
"`Email or Username` box and press `forgot password`. If everything is set up "
"correctly, you should receive an email to renew your password. You can "
"ignore this email."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/first_steps.md:21
msgid "Federation"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/first_steps.md:23
msgid ""
"Federation is disabled by default, and needs to be enabled either through "
"the online admin panel or directly through the `config.json` file."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/first_steps.md:25
msgid ""
"To test that your instance federation is working correctly execute `curl -H "
"'Accept: application/activity+json' https://your-instance.com/u/your-"
"username`, it should return json data, and not an .html file. If that is "
"unclear to you, it should look similar to the output of `curl -H 'Accept: "
"application/activity+json' https://lemmy.ml/u/nutomic`."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/first_steps.md:27
msgid "Inclusion on join-lemmy.org instance list"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/first_steps.md:29
msgid ""
"To be included in the list of Lemmy instances on [join-lemmy.org](https://"
"join-lemmy.org/instances) you must meet the following requirements:"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/first_steps.md:31
msgid "Federate with at least one instance from the list"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/first_steps.md:32
msgid "Have a site description and icon"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/first_steps.md:33
msgid ""
"Make sure you require registration applications. This helps keep bots and "
"trolls from using your server to spam the fediverse."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/first_steps.md:34
msgid ""
"Have at least 5 users who posted or commented at least once in the past month"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/first_steps.md:35
msgid "Be on the latest major version of Lemmy"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/first_steps.md:36
msgid ""
"Be patient and wait the site to be updated, there's no fixed schedule for "
"that"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/first_steps.md:38
msgid ""
"Recommended instances are defined in code [here](https://github.com/LemmyNet/"
"joinlemmy-site/blob/main/recommended-instances.json) and the code that "
"powers the crawler is visible [here](https://github.com/LemmyNet/lemmy-stats-"
"crawler)."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/first_steps.md:41
msgid ""
"In the meantime you can always promote your server on other social networks "
"like Mastodon using the hashtag `#Lemmy`."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/first_steps.md:43
msgid "Keeping up to date"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/first_steps.md:45
msgid ""
"You can subscribe to the Github RSS feeds to be informed of the latest "
"releases:"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/first_steps.md:47
msgid "[lemmy](https://github.com/LemmyNet/lemmy/releases.atom)"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/first_steps.md:48
msgid "[lemmy-ui](https://github.com/LemmyNet/lemmy-ui/releases.atom)"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/first_steps.md:49
msgid ""
"[lemmy-js-client](https://github.com/LemmyNet/lemmy-js-client/releases.atom)"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/first_steps.md:50
msgid ""
"[joinlemmy-site](https://github.com/LemmyNet/joinlemmy-site/releases.atom)"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/first_steps.md:52
msgid ""
"There is also a [Matrix chat](https://matrix.to/#/#lemmy-admin-support-"
"topics:discuss.online) for instance administrators that you can join. You'll "
"find some really friendly people there who will help you (or at least try "
"to) if you run into any issue."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/federation_getting_started.md:1
msgid "Getting started with Federation"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/federation_getting_started.md:3
msgid ""
"Federation is enabled by default, but initially you won't see any content "
"from other Lemmy instances. To get started you can browse [other Lemmy "
"instances](https://join-lemmy.org/instances) for interesting communities, or "
"browse the community list on [lemmyverse.net](https://lemmyverse.net/"
"communities). Once you find an interesting community, simply paste the URL "
"into the search field on your own Lemmy instance, for example `https://lemmy."
"ml/c/announcements`. To have new content in the community pushed to your "
"instance, you need to click the \"Follow\" button in the sidebar."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/federation_getting_started.md:5
msgid ""
"If you notice that community follows are still shown as \"Subscription "
"Pending\" after a few hours, or your posts are not visible on other "
"instances, you may have a configuration problem. Check out the "
"[troubleshooting guide](troubleshooting.md), you can also ask for help in [!"
"lemmy@lemmy.ml](https://lemmy.ml/c/lemmy) or the [admin chat on Matrix]"
"(https://matrix.to/#/#lemmy-support-general:discuss.online)."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/federation_getting_started.md:7
msgid "Fetching Data"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/federation_getting_started.md:9
msgid ""
"If you see something interesting while browsing another Lemmy instance, you "
"can easily import it in order to interact with the content. This works for "
"users, communities, posts and comments. For posts and comments, you can get "
"the correct URL from the colorful \"Fedilink\" icon. All of the following "
"formats are valid to fetch data over federation:"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/federation_getting_started.md:11
msgid "`https://lemmy.ml/c/programming` (Community)"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/federation_getting_started.md:12
msgid "`https://lemmy.ml/u/nutomic` (User)"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/federation_getting_started.md:13
msgid "`https://lemmy.ml/post/123` (Post)"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/federation_getting_started.md:14
msgid "`https://lemmy.ml/comment/321` (Comment)"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/federation_getting_started.md:15
msgid "`!main@lemmy.ml` (Community)"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/federation_getting_started.md:16
msgid "`@nutomic@lemmy.ml` (User)"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/federation_getting_started.md:18
msgid ""
"When fetching a community, the most recent posts are also fetched "
"automatically (but not comments or votes). When fetching a post, the "
"community and author are also fetched automatically. And for comments, all "
"parent comments, the post, their respective authors and the community are "
"fetched. Sibling comments are not fetched automatically. If you want more "
"comments from older posts, you have to search for each of them as described "
"above."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/federation_getting_started.md:20
msgid ""
"You can also fetch content from other Fediverse platforms such as [Piefed]"
"(https://join.piefed.social/) or [Mbin](https://joinmbin.org/). Other "
"platforms may also work, but only if they use communities like Lemmy."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/federation_getting_started.md:22
msgid "Blocking or Allowing Instances"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/federation_getting_started.md:24
msgid "Lemmy has three types of federation:"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/federation_getting_started.md:26
msgid "Allowlist: Explicitly list instances to connect to."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/federation_getting_started.md:27
msgid ""
"BlockList: Explicitly list instances to not connect to. Federation is open "
"to all other instances."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/federation_getting_started.md:28
msgid "Open: Federate with all potential instances."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/federation_getting_started.md:30
msgid ""
"You can add allowed and blocked instances, by adding a list in your instance "
"admin panel. IE to only federate with these instances, add: `enterprise."
"lemmy.ml,lemmy.ml` to the allowed instances section."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/federation_getting_started.md:32
msgid ""
"Lemmy uses the ActivityPub protocol (a W3C standard) to enable federation "
"between different servers (often called instances). This is very similar to "
"the way email works. For example, if you use gmail.com, then you can not "
"only send mails to other gmail.com users, but also to yahoo.com, yandex.ru "
"and so on. Email uses the SMTP protocol to achieve this, so you can think of "
"ActivityPub as \"SMTP for social media\". The many of different actions "
"possible on social media (post, comment, like, share, etc) make that "
"ActivityPub is much more complicated than SMTP."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/federation_getting_started.md:34
msgid ""
"As with email, ActivityPub federation happens only between servers. So if "
"you are registered on `enterprise.lemmy.ml`, you only connect to the API of "
"`enterprise.lemmy.ml`, while the server takes care of sending and receiving "
"data from other instances (eg `voyager.lemmy.ml`). The great advantage of "
"this approach is that the average user doesn't have to do anything to use "
"federation. In fact if you are using Lemmy, you are likely already using it. "
"One way to confirm is by going to a community or user profile. If you are on "
"`enterprise.lemmy.ml` and you see a user like `@nutomic@voyager.lemmy.ml`, "
"or a community like `!main@ds9.lemmy.ml`, then those are federated, meaning "
"they use a different instance from yours."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:1
msgid "Horizontal Scaling"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:3
msgid ""
"This is a collection of notes on scaling different Lemmy components "
"horizontally. This is not meant as a step-by-step guide, rather as general "
"tips and knowledge that might be useful to somebody who is already familiar "
"with and horizontal scaling concepts and best practices. If you don't "
"already know about concepts like load balancing, object storage, and reverse "
"proxies, then this document will probably be hard (or impossible) to "
"understand."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:5
msgid ""
"**Note: scaling Lemmy this way is not necessary, and for small instances, "
"the added overhead most likely outweighs any benefits.**"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:7
msgid "Why scale horizontally?"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:9
msgid ""
"If one of your Lemmy servers dies for any reason, your instance can still "
"remain operational"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:10
msgid ""
"Having multiple Lemmy servers allows you to do rolling upgrades (no downtime "
"needed to upgrade Lemmy!)"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:11
msgid ""
"Horizontal scaling provides additional flexibility in how you upgrade your "
"infrastructure"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:12
msgid ""
"As of Lemmy version 0.18.2, Lemmy appears to be able to use the same "
"resources more efficiently if they are split between multiple Lemmy processes"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:14
msgid "Breakdown of Lemmy components"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:16
msgid ""
"See [Lemmy components](administration.md#lemmy-components) for a high level "
"overview of what each component does."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:20
msgid ""
"Lemmy-ui can be horizontally scaled, but make sure you read the following "
"section for information about rolling upgrades."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:22
#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:102
msgid "Rolling upgrades"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:24
msgid ""
"In general, there is nothing preventing you from running multiple load "
"balanced Lemmy-ui servers in parallel, but without some custom "
"configuration, **rolling upgrades will break Lemmy for your users!** This is "
"because by default, Lemmy-ui will serve static files through the express "
"process."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:26
msgid ""
"Consider the scenario where you have 2 Lemmy-ui servers, one is running on "
"version 1, and the other has just come online running version 2. A user "
"opening your Lemmy in their browser might have their front page html request "
"routed to version 1. This html will contain a reference to many other static "
"files which are specific to version 1. Most likely, some of these requests "
"will get routed to the server running version 2. **The files will not exist "
"on this server, the server will respond with 404, and the UI will remain in "
"a broken state.**"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:28
msgid "There are a few ways to work around this issue:"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:30
msgid ""
"The safest option is to ensure that all servers are able to serve static "
"files for all currently active Lemmy-ui versions."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:31
msgid ""
"There are many ways to achieve this, the most obvious one being to upload "
"your static files to object storage, and have reverse proxies route static "
"file requests to your static files bucket."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:32
msgid "Here's one possible example of how to do this with nginx:"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:34
msgid ""
"```\n"
"location /static {\n"
"   expires 1y;\n"
"   add_header Cache-Control \"public\";\n"
"   proxy_pass https://${bucket_fqdn};\n"
"\n"
"   limit_except GET {\n"
"       deny  all;\n"
"   }\n"
"\n"
"   proxy_intercept_errors on;\n"
"   # invalid keys result in 403\n"
"   error_page 403 =404 /@404static;\n"
"}\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:50
msgid ""
"Replace `${bucket_fqdn}` with the URL to your bucket. With this setup, you "
"should upload the contents of the lemmy-ui `dist/` directory to a "
"\"directory\" named `static/$LEMMY_UI_HASH` in your bucket, where the hash "
"is calculated from the commit you are deploying: `export LEMMY_UI_HASH=$(git "
"rev-parse --short HEAD)`. Note that this setup requires public acl on "
"uploaded files, so it's recommended to limit access to your bucket with an "
"IP allowlist policy."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:52
msgid ""
"An alternative option is to configure sticky sessions in your load balancer. "
"This will ensure that subsequent requests all end up on the same Lemmy-ui "
"server, and as long as your sticky sessions last longer than your upgrade "
"process, most clients should remain functional."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:53
msgid ""
"Similarly to sticky sessions, another possibility is to configure ip hash "
"based load balancing."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:54
msgid ""
"There is always the option to just employ downtime and upgrade all servers "
"at once (but that's not very fun!)"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:58
msgid "Lemmy_server can be horizontally scaled, with a few caveats."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:60
msgid ""
"Here's a quick example on how you could start 3 web servers, 3 federation "
"servers and one scheduled task process:"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:67
msgid ""
"Or run the Docker container with the `-e LEMMY_DISABLE_HTTP_SERVER=true` and "
"`-e LEMMY_DISABLE_ACTIVITY_SENDING=true` ENV parameters."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:76
msgid ""
"Or run the Docker containers with the `-e "
"LEMMY_DISABLE_ACTIVITY_SENDING=true` and `-e "
"LEMMY_DISABLE_SCHEDULED_TASKS=true` ENV parameters."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:85
msgid ""
"Or run the Docker containers with the `-e LEMMY_DISABLE_HTTP_SERVER=true`, `-"
"e LEMMY_DISABLE_SCHEDULED_TASKS=true`, `-e LEMMY_FEDERATE_PROCESS_INDEX=1` "
"and `-e LEMMY_FEDERATE_PROCESS_COUNT=3` ENV parameters."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:87
msgid "Scheduled tasks"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:89
msgid ""
"By default, a Lemmy_server process will run background scheduled tasks, "
"which must be run only on one server. Launching multiple processes with the "
"default configuration will result in multiple duplicated scheduled tasks all "
"starting at the same moment and trying to do the same thing at once."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:91
msgid ""
"To solve this, Lemmy must be started with the `--disable-scheduled-tasks` "
"flag (or `LEMMY_DISABLE_SCHEDULED_TASKS=true`) on all but one instance. In "
"general, there are two approaches:"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:93
msgid ""
"Run all your load balanced Lemmy servers with the `--disable-scheduled-"
"tasks` flag, and run one additional Lemmy server without this flag which is "
"not in your load balancer and does not accept any HTTP traffic."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:94
msgid ""
"Run one load balanced Lemmy server without the flag, and all other load "
"balanced servers with the flag."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:96
msgid "Federation queue"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:98
msgid ""
"The persistent federation queue (since 0.19) is split by federated domain "
"and can be processed in equal-size parts run in separate processes. To split "
"the queue up into N processes numbered 1...N, use the arguments `--federate-"
"process-index=i --federate-process-count=N` on each (or "
"`LEMMY_FEDERATE_PROCESS_INDEX=i` and `LEMMY_FEDERATE_PROCESS_COUNT=N` "
"respectively). It is important that each index is is given to exactly one "
"process, otherwise you will get undefined behaviour (missing, dupe "
"federation, crashes)."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:100
msgid ""
"Federation processes can be started and stopped at will. They will restart "
"federation to each instance from the last transmitted activity regardless of "
"downtime."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:104
msgid ""
"For most versions, rolling releases have been completely OK, but there have "
"been some cases where a database migration slips in which is NOT backwards "
"compatible (causing any servers running the older version of Lemmy to "
"potentially start generating errors). To be safe, you should always first "
"take a look at [what database migrations are included in a new version]"
"(https://github.com/LemmyNet/lemmy/tree/main/migrations), and evaluate "
"whether the changes are for sure safe to apply with running servers."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:106
msgid ""
"Note that even if there are no backwards incompatible migrations between "
"immediate version upgrades (version 1 -> 2 is safe and 2 -> 3 is safe), "
"doing bigger upgrades might cause these same migrations to become backwards "
"incompatible (a server running version 1 might not be compatible with "
"migrations from version 3 in this scenario). **It is generally best to only "
"upgrade one version at a time!**."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:108
msgid ""
"For the scheduled task process, it shouldn't cause any major issues to have "
"two servers running in parallel for a short duration during an upgrade, but "
"shutting the old one down before starting the new one will always be safer."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:112
msgid ""
"Pict-rs does not scale horizontally as of writing this document. This is due "
"to a dependency on a Sled database, which is a disk based database file."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:114
msgid ""
"The developer of pict-rs has mentioned plans to eventually add Postgres "
"support (which should in theory enable horizontal scaling), but work on this "
"has not yet started."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:116
msgid ""
"Note that by caching pict-rs images (for example, with nginx, or with a "
"CDN), you can really minimize load on the pict-rs server!"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:118
msgid "Other tips"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:120
msgid ""
"Your lemmy-ui servers need to access your backend as well. If you don't want "
"a complicated setup with multiple load balancers, you could just have each "
"of your servers contain nginx, lemmy-ui, and lemmy_server, and just load "
"balance to an nginx on each of your servers"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:121
msgid ""
"Make sure you're passing the real client ip address to Lemmy, otherwise "
"Lemmy's built in rate limiter will trigger very often (if it rate limits "
"based on your load balancer's IP address, for example). With nginx, you "
"should use something like this in your nginx.conf:"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/horizontal_scaling.md:129
msgid ""
"The internal Lemmy load balancer works based on an in-memory storage of ip "
"addresses. That means that by adding more Lemmy servers, you are effectively "
"making your rate limits less strict. If you rely on the built in limiter, "
"make sure to adjust the limits accordingly!"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/from_scratch.md:1
msgid "Install from Scratch"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/from_scratch.md:3
msgid ""
"These instructions are written for Ubuntu 20.04 / Ubuntu 22.04. They are "
"particularly useful when you'd like to setup a Lemmy container (e.g. LXC on "
"Proxmox) and cannot use Docker."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/from_scratch.md:5
msgid ""
"Lemmy is built from source in this guide, so this may take a while, "
"especially on slow devices. For example, Lemmy v0.18.5 takes around 7 "
"minutes to build on a quad core VPS."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/from_scratch.md:7
msgid ""
"Installing and configuring Lemmy using this guide takes about 60-90 minutes. "
"You might need to make yourself a fresh cup of coffee before you start."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/from_scratch.md:9
msgid "Installation"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/from_scratch.md:11
msgid "Database"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/from_scratch.md:13
msgid ""
"For Ubuntu 20.04 the shipped PostgreSQL version is 12 which is not supported "
"by Lemmy. So let's set up a newer one. The most recent stable version of "
"PostgreSQL is 16 at the time of writing this guide."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/from_scratch.md:16 src/administration/from_scratch.md:212
#: src/administration/from_scratch.md:289
msgid "Install dependencies"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/from_scratch.md:18
msgid ""
"```\n"
"sudo apt install -y wget ca-certificates pkg-config\n"
"wget --quiet -O - https://www.postgresql.org/media/keys/ACCC4CF8.asc | sudo "
"apt-key add -\n"
"sudo sh -c 'echo \"deb http://apt.postgresql.org/pub/repos/apt/ "
"$(lsb_release -cs)-pgdg main\" >> /etc/apt/sources.list.d/pgdg.list'\n"
"sudo apt update\n"
"sudo apt install libssl-dev libpq-dev postgresql\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/from_scratch.md:26
msgid "Setup Lemmy database"
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/from_scratch.md:28
msgid ""
"Replace db-passwd with a unique password of your choice in the commands "
"below."
msgstr ""

#: src/administration/from_scratch.md:30
msgid ""
"```\n"
"sudo -iu postgres psql -c \"CREATE USER lemmy WITH PASSWORD 'db-passwd';\"\n"
