#: src/contributors/07-ranking-algo.md:1
msgid "Ranking Algorithm"
msgstr ""

#: src/contributors/07-ranking-algo.md:3
msgid "Goals"
msgstr ""

#: src/contributors/07-ranking-algo.md:5
msgid ""
"During the day, new posts and comments should be near the top, so they can "
"be voted on."
msgstr ""

#: src/contributors/07-ranking-algo.md:6
msgid "After a day or so, the time factor should go away."
msgstr ""

#: src/contributors/07-ranking-algo.md:7
msgid ""
"Use a log scale, since votes tend to snowball, and so the first 10 votes are "
"just as important as the next hundred."
msgstr ""

#: src/contributors/07-ranking-algo.md:9
msgid "Implementations"
msgstr ""

#: src/contributors/07-ranking-algo.md:11
msgid "Reddit"
msgstr ""

#: src/contributors/07-ranking-algo.md:13
msgid ""
"Does not take the lifetime of the thread into account, [giving early "
"comments an overwhelming advantage over later ones,](https://minimaxir."
"com/2016/11/first-comment/) with the effect being even worse in small "
"communities. New comments pool at the bottom of the thread, effectively "
"killing off discussion and making each thread a race to comment early. This "
"lowers the quality of conversation and rewards comments that are repetitive "
"and spammy."
msgstr ""

#: src/contributors/07-ranking-algo.md:15
msgid "Hacker News"
msgstr ""

#: src/contributors/07-ranking-algo.md:17
msgid ""
"While far superior to Reddit's implementation for its decay of scores over "
"time, [Hacker News' ranking algorithm](https://medium.com/hacking-and-gonzo/"
"how-hacker-news-ranking-algorithm-works-1d9b0cf2c08d) does not use a "
"logarithmic scale for scores."
msgstr ""

#: src/contributors/07-ranking-algo.md:21
msgid ""
"Counterbalances the snowballing effect of votes over time with a logarithmic "
"scale. Negates the inherent advantage of early comments while still ensuring "
"that votes still matter in the long-term, not nuking older popular comments."
msgstr ""

#: src/contributors/07-ranking-algo.md:33
msgid ""
"Lemmy uses the same `Rank` algorithm above, in three sorts: `Active`, `Hot`, "
"and `Scaled`."
msgstr ""

#: src/contributors/07-ranking-algo.md:34
msgid ""
"`Active` uses the post votes, and latest comment time (limited to two days)."
msgstr ""

#: src/contributors/07-ranking-algo.md:35
msgid "`Hot` uses the post votes, and the post published time."
msgstr ""

#: src/contributors/07-ranking-algo.md:36
msgid ""
"`Scaled` is similar to `Hot`, but gives a boost to smaller / less active "
"communities."
msgstr ""

#: src/contributors/07-ranking-algo.md:37
msgid "Use Max(1, score) to make sure all comments are affected by time decay."
msgstr ""

#: src/contributors/07-ranking-algo.md:38
msgid ""
"Add 3 to the score, so that everything that has less than 3 downvotes will "
"seem new. Otherwise all new comments would stay at zero, near the bottom."
msgstr ""

#: src/contributors/07-ranking-algo.md:39
msgid ""
"The sign and abs of the score are necessary for dealing with the log of "
"negative scores."
msgstr ""

#: src/contributors/07-ranking-algo.md:40
msgid "A scale factor of 10k gets the rank in integer form."
msgstr ""

#: src/contributors/07-ranking-algo.md:42
msgid ""
"A plot of rank over 24 hours, of scores of 1, 5, 10, 100, 1000, with a scale "
"factor of 10k."
msgstr ""

#: src/contributors/07-ranking-algo.md:44
msgid "![rank_algorithm.png](rank_algorithm.png)"
msgstr ""

#: src/contributors/07-ranking-algo.md:46
msgid "Active User counts"
msgstr ""

#: src/contributors/07-ranking-algo.md:48
msgid ""
"Lemmy also shows counts of _active users_ for your site, and its "
"communities. These are counted within the last `day`, `week`, `month`, and "
"`half year`, and are cached on starting up lemmy, and every hour."
msgstr ""

#: src/contributors/07-ranking-algo.md:50
msgid ""
"An active user is someone who has posted, commented, or voted on our "
"instance or community within the last given time frame. For site counts, "
"only local users are counted. For community counts, federated users are "
"included."
msgstr ""

